      &lt;td width=&quot;2%&quot; style=word-wrap:break-word&gt; xyz@gmail.com &lt;/td&gt;
      &lt;td width=&quot;2%&quot;&gt; filename1 &lt;/td&gt;
    &lt;/tr&gt;

If this is the case, the XPath below will work

    //tr[./td[.=&#39; filename1 &#39;]][./td[.=&#39; 10/04/2019 &#39;]]/td/input

If you plan to reuse this locator with other filenames and dates, I would insert variables into the locator. There are [many, many ways](https://stackoverflow.com/a/2962966/2386774) to insert a variable into a string using python. If you are using python 3.6, you can use the [formatted string literals](https://docs.python.org/3/whatsnew/3.6.html#whatsnew36-pep498) below, as an example.

    //tr[./td[.=&#39; {filename} &#39;]][./td[.=&#39; {date} &#39;]]/td/input

Now you can create a method and pass in the filename and date and return the correct `INPUT` easily.

